data.name: label23.Text
data.value: - The polarizer can be rotated so that different polarization is selected. It is highly recommended to have the polarizer either completely parallel or perpendicular to the beam to eliminate source of error. It should also be noted that beamsplitters have different performance based off the polarization of the incident beam.

data.name: label22.Text
data.value: - The beam splitter used has a ratio of 70T:30R (Should it ever need to be replaced). More power needs to be transmitted to the sample power meter since using higher OD filters will decrease the amount of power transmitted significantly. The power sensor performs better when not operating at limit conditions.

data.name: label21.Text
data.value: - It was determined by testing that the most useful data count setting is 100 for both the reference and the sample. Less than this showed higher error, and a higher count took signifcantly longer for relatively little gain in accuracy.

data.name: label19.Text
data.value: - Additionally, if the time interval setting is used in conjunction with the step averaging the time between measuremements is the time between each individual measurement, not the block (averaged) measurements. Thus, with or without step averaging the system will take roughly the same time with the time interval setting activated.

data.name: label18.Text
data.value: - Step averaging in this context means that the system will take multiple measurements and then average them to create one measurement. For example, if a setting of 20 steps per average is chosen with an overall count of 100 samples, the system will show that "5" measurements were taken. Realistically, the system still takes 100 samples, just broken down into blocks of 20 samples.
